=========================================
C++17 std::optional
INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::optional?

std::optional is a C++17 feature that represents an object that may or may not contain a value.

Instead of returning special values like

-1

0

nullptr

or an empty string to indicate failure, std::optional explicitly represents "a value may exist" or "no value".

Header

#include <optional>

Syntax

std::optional<T>

-----------------------------------------

2. Why was std::optional introduced?

Before C++17

int find()
{
    return -1;
}

Problem

Suppose

-1

is a valid value.

How do we know whether

-1

means

"Not Found"

or

"The actual value is -1"

This ambiguity is called using a "magic value".

std::optional solves this problem.

-----------------------------------------

3. C++17 Solution

#include <optional>

optional<int> find()
{
    return 10;
}

int main()
{
    auto x = find();

    if(x)
        cout << *x;
}

Output

10

-----------------------------------------

4. Returning "No Value"

optional<int> find()
{
    return {};
}

or

optional<int> find()
{
    return nullopt;
}

Usage

auto x = find();

if(x)
{
    cout << *x;
}
else
{
    cout << "No Value";
}

Output

No Value

-----------------------------------------

5. What happens internally?

optional<int>

contains

• Storage for an int
• A boolean flag indicating whether a value exists

Conceptually

optional<int>

+------------------+
| hasValue = true  |
| value = 10       |
+------------------+

or

+------------------+
| hasValue = false |
| no value         |
+------------------+

-----------------------------------------

6. How to check whether a value exists?

Method 1 (Most Common)

if(opt)
{
    cout << *opt;
}

Method 2

if(opt.has_value())
{
    cout << opt.value();
}

-----------------------------------------

7. Accessing the value

Using *

cout << *opt;

Using value()

cout << opt.value();

Note

Calling

value()

when no value exists throws

std::bad_optional_access

-----------------------------------------

8. Default Value

optional<int> find()
{
    return {};
}

cout << find().value_or(100);

Output

100

If the optional is empty,

value_or()

returns the supplied default value.

-----------------------------------------

9. Example

#include <iostream>
#include <optional>
using namespace std;

optional<int> divide(int a,int b)
{
    if(b==0)
        return nullopt;

    return a/b;
}

int main()
{
    auto ans = divide(20,5);

    if(ans)
        cout << *ans;
    else
        cout << "Division by zero";
}

Output

4

-----------------------------------------

10. Member Functions

has_value()

Checks whether a value exists.

--------------------------------

value()

Returns the stored value.

Throws an exception if empty.

--------------------------------

value_or(default)

Returns stored value.

Otherwise returns the default.

--------------------------------

reset()

Removes the stored value.

Example

opt.reset();

--------------------------------

emplace()

Constructs a new value in place.

Example

opt.emplace(50);

-----------------------------------------

11. Advantages

• Eliminates magic values

• Makes APIs clearer

• Expresses optional return values

• Safer than nullptr

• Better readability

-----------------------------------------

