13. Interview Questions

Q. What is std::optional?

Answer

std::optional is a C++17 wrapper that represents an object which may or may not contain a value.

-----------------------------------------

Q. Which C++ version introduced std::optional?

Answer

C++17

-----------------------------------------

Q. What problem does std::optional solve?

Answer

Before C++17, functions often returned special values like -1, nullptr, or empty strings to indicate 
failure. These "magic values" could also be valid results, causing ambiguity. std::optional removes 
this ambiguity by explicitly representing the presence or absence of a value.

-----------------------------------------

Q. How do you check whether an optional contains a value?

Answer

Method 1

if(opt)

Method 2

if(opt.has_value())

-----------------------------------------

Q. How do you access the stored value?

Answer

Using

*opt

or

opt.value()

-----------------------------------------

Q. What is value_or()?

Answer

value_or(default)

returns the stored value if present; otherwise it returns the specified default value.

Example

cout << opt.value_or(100);

-----------------------------------------

Q. What happens if value() is called on an empty optional?

Answer

It throws

std::bad_optional_access

-----------------------------------------

Q. Difference between std::optional and nullptr?

Answer

nullptr represents the absence of an object pointer.

std::optional can represent the absence of any type, including int, double, string, or user-defined classes.

-----------------------------------------

14. Interview Explanation (30 Seconds)

"std::optional was introduced in C++17 to represent values that may or may not exist. Instead of 
returning magic values like -1 or nullptr, a function returns std::optional<T>. The caller checks 
whether a value exists using if(optional) or has_value(), and then accesses it using *optional or 
value(). This makes APIs safer, more expressive, and eliminates ambiguity."

